<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12009f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12009f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12009f"> 9(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Irrfahrten</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Not found as such in source, but maybe inspired by the discussion on pp.144-5 about causing confusion by simplifying the general drift of great writers. Baudelaire&apos;s <cite>Les Fleurs du Mal</cite> has the reputation of being a libidinous book; it isn&apos;t, but this reputation causes it to be read. Therefore: &ldquo;La meilleure inspiration que puisse avoir un auteur, c&apos;est donc d&apos;inventer une formule, de pincer une guitare, de lancer un bateau.&rdquo; <font color="green">[the best inspiration an author can have, is to invent a formula, of strumming a guitar, of launching a boat]</font> So you have to take the public on an <i>Irrfahrt</i> <font color="green">[wild-goose chase]</font> to make them read. <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) ?144-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
